= The Discovery Phase

The Discovery Phase refers to the period during which a small private research group identified and experimentally validated a set of anomalous physical processes that would later underpin the technological foundations of Luminous. This phase spans from early 2025, when the first repeatable experimental anomalies were observed, to late 2031, when their implications became clear enough to necessitate full political and geographic withdrawal from Earth-based systems.

Initial research during this period was not directed toward post-scarcity outcomes or civilisational transformation. The work originated within a media and technology company primarily engaged in the creation of speculative media and fictional science-fiction worlds, alongside commercial activity in consumer electronics and computational optimisation. Early experiments emerged indirectly from performance-focused research into particle behaviour, energy efficiency, and simulation fidelity, driven by practical constraints rather than theoretical ambition.

By mid-2027, researchers documented a class of reactions capable of assembling complex molecular structures directly from simple atmospheric inputs, most notably carbon dioxide, using only electrical energy as an initiating resource. These reactions exhibited unusually high efficiency, stability across multiple scales, and a level of controllability inconsistent with established physical models. Further investigation revealed that under specific configurations, the system could produce surplus electrical energy and carbon dioxide relative to its inputs, enabling closed-loop operation without environmental extraction.

Throughout 2027 and 2028, parallel research confirmed that the same underlying process could be miniaturised or expanded without loss of stability. Applications ranged from micro-scale fabrication to room-scale material synthesis, effectively collapsing the distinction between energy generation, manufacturing, and resource acquisition. During this period, advances in solid-state quantum computation (enabled by the same material and energy properties) dramatically accelerated simulation, modelling, and system control capabilities.

Between 2029 and 2030, high-fidelity simulations made possible by these computational advances enabled sustained investigation into relativistic constraints on space travel. Researchers identified methods to mitigate temporal divergence effects at velocities approaching the speed of light, allowing for rapid interstellar transit without extreme temporal displacement relative to Earth. These results were initially confined to simulation and controlled experimental validation.

As experimental confidence increased, internal assessments shifted from technical feasibility to systemic risk. By late 2030, it was recognised that deployment of these technologies within existing Earth-based political, economic, and military structures would destabilise global systems faster than governance frameworks could adapt. Particular concern was raised regarding irreversible cybersecurity collapse, structural economic asymmetry, and the militarisation of abundance-capable infrastructure.

In early 2031, the research leadership reached a consensus that incremental disclosure, regulation, or partial deployment would be insufficient to mitigate these risks. The technologies could not be selectively introduced without triggering competitive escalation, nor could they be reliably contained once knowledge spread beyond a tightly controlled group. The conclusion drawn was that Earth, as it then existed, lacked the legislative, ethical, and cognitive structures necessary to safely interface with such capabilities.

The Discovery Phase formally ended in November 2031, when the decision was made to remove all active development, physical prototypes, and core personnel from Earth jurisdiction entirely. Planning for off-world withdrawal began immediately thereafter, marking the transition into what would later be known as the Off-World Withdrawal period.